instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin lifecycle follows the MBSE development chain split into abstraction levels: (1) requirements modeling, (2) functional architecture, (3) logical architecture, and (4) product/technical layer. At each stage the twin is represented by corresponding models – requirements captured in SysML requirement diagrams, functional blocks in SysML internal block diagrams or ADL component‑connector graphs, logical behavior encoded in state‑machine or automaton extensions (e.g., MontiArc Automaton), and detailed product models in simulation tools such as Simulink or executable code (C++, Java). Transition between stages is managed by integrating heterogeneous stakeholder models and by mapping components across notations, while governance follows the MBSE practice of traceability across the RFLP (Requirements, Functions, Logics, Physics) methodology."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin adopts several established modeling standards: SysML (OMG), Architecture Description Languages such as ACME, AADL (ASME/OMG), and MontiArc, as well as simulation standards embodied in MathWorks Simulink. These standards provide a common semantics for component‑connector structures, interfaces and behavior description, enabling interoperability between tools and stakeholders. No specific certification or regulatory compliance frameworks are mentioned."
]
